President Donald Trump has proclaimed March 3-9, 2019, as National Consumer Protection Week. In his proclamation, he highlights the importance of consumer knowledge in navigating the market economy and protecting against fraudulent and deceptive financial practices. He emphasizes the need for vigilance when providing personal information online, over the phone, or by mail, and encourages individuals to keep their software up to date. The President also mentions the steps his administration has taken to strengthen consumer protections, such as the Economic Growth, Regulatory Relief, and Consumer Protection Act and the establishment of the Task Force on Market Integrity and Consumer Fraud. He urges individuals, businesses, organizations, government agencies, and community groups to make use of online resources provided by the Federal Trade Commission and Consumer Financial Protection Bureau to educate themselves and others about consumer protection.